```

You see that they effectively do the same thing, they call a method for each entry in the global list of available connections.
The parameter `layOverVertex` in `showConnections` is completely unused, but  you should filter the `HWGraph g` by the layover.

Then compare your methods `show` and `connect`, `show` is used for the global list of connections, while `connect` should show the connections starting in the layover city and also add the distance to get there to all distances:

``` lang-java
private static void show(String key, ArrayList&lt;Vertex&gt; value) {
  System.out.println(&quot;Showing connections for key: &quot; + key + &quot;--------&quot;);
  for(Vertex v : value){
    System.out.println(&quot;City: &quot; + v.label + &quot; Distance: &quot; + v.weight);
  }
}

private static void connect(String key, ArrayList&lt;Vertex&gt; value) {
  for (Vertex v : value) {
    System.out.println(&quot;City: &quot; + v.label + &quot; Distance: &quot; + v.weight);
  }
}
```
You see that the methods are quite similar, just `show` prints an additional header, otherwise they are equal. 
Notice that the parameter `key` is only used in the `show` method to print the header, it is completely unused in the `connect` method. Also the `connect` method doesn&#39;t know about the distance to add - there is no parameter for that.

So what you are missing is:

* filter the full map of connections by the layover city (hint: `Map.entrySet()` provides you with a set of all entries in the map)
* add the distance from the starting city to the layover city (initial distance) as parameter to the `connect` method, add a third value to the output that displays the sum of the initial distance and the distance to the target
* remove the parameter `key` from the `connect` method if you don&#39;t need it there (e.g. for some additional output)

